      <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4 ">1. Bright Colors: Grabbing Attention and Sparking Energy</h3>
      <p class="w-100 lead">Bright colors are the life of the party when it comes to advertising design. They’re bold, vibrant, and impossible to ignore. If your brand is all about fun, excitement, or high energy, bright colors can be your secret weapon. Think of brands like McDonald’s, with its iconic red and yellow, or Spotify’s bold greens and purples—they’re designed to grab your attention instantly.<br/><br/>
        For startups and small businesses in niches like entertainment, tech, or retail, bright colors can be a great choice. They convey enthusiasm and confidence, which can make your brand feel approachable and dynamic. Picture an Instagram ad for a summer festival. Bright yellows and oranges scream “fun” and “warmth,” making viewers stop mid-scroll to learn more.<br/><br/>
        But don’t go overboard. Too many bright colors can feel chaotic and overwhelming. The key is to pair one or two bold hues with neutral tones to balance your design. This way, your ad stays eye-catching without becoming a sensory overload.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col">
      <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">2. Subtle Tones: Sophistication and Trust</h3>
      <p class="w-100 lead">If bright colors are the party animal, subtle tones are the elegant dinner guest. These colors, like soft blues, muted greens, and gentle grays, create a sense of calm, professionalism, and trust. They’re ideal for niches like healthcare, finance, or luxury goods, where customers value reliability and sophistication over excitement.<br/><br/>
        Let’s say you’re running an advertising design campaign for a boutique skincare brand. Subtle tones like pastel pinks or soft beiges can evoke feelings of self-care and comfort. These colors say, “We’re here to help you relax,” which is exactly the vibe you want for this type of product.<br/><br/>
        Subtle tones are also great for conveying modern minimalism. If your brand identity leans towards clean and sleek aesthetics, subtle hues can reinforce that message. They work particularly well for B2B industries, where the goal is to build trust rather than stand out with loud visuals.
        </p>
    </div>
    </div>
    </div>
