          <div class="col">
            <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">3. Match Colors to Your Audience’s Preferences</h3>
            <p class="w-100 lead">The right color choice often depends on your audience and what they expect from your brand. Bright colors are fantastic for targeting younger demographics who are drawn to energy and playfulness. Think of a trendy startup targeting Gen Z—neon greens and hot pinks can be a hit.<br/><br/>
              On the other hand, subtle tones often resonate more with older audiences or professionals who value calm and clarity. A subtle navy or gray might work wonders for a financial planning service aiming to build trust with a mature audience.<br/><br/>
              Cultural factors also play a role. Colors carry different meanings in different cultures, so it’s important to consider your audience’s background. For example, red symbolizes luck in Chinese culture but can convey danger in Western contexts. Always keep your audience in mind when choosing your color palette.
              </p>
      </div>
      <div class="col">
        <h3 class="fw-bold text-secondary mt-4">4. Testing and Finding the Right Balance</h3>
        <p class="w-100 lead">If you’re unsure whether bright colors or subtle tones will work best, let data guide you. A/B testing is a fantastic way to experiment with different color schemes. Create two versions of your ad—one with bold, vibrant tones and another with muted, calming hues. Let them run simultaneously and track which one performs better.<br/><br/>
          For example, a food delivery startup might test a bold red-and-yellow ad versus a subtle green-and-white design. The results could reveal which palette resonates more with their audience, helping them refine their advertising design strategy.<br/><br/>
          Sometimes, the best approach is to combine bright colors and subtle tones. Use a bold accent color to draw attention to your call-to-action while keeping the rest of the design soft and professional. This balance can give you the best of both worlds, appealing to a wide audience without alienating anyone.          
          </p>
